  "response_text": "The simulation of the mean deviation between agents' held health values and implied choice values demonstrates a consistent upward trajectory over the 33 time steps. The metric begins at 0.0000 and rises to a maximum of 0.7251 at the final time step 32. Statistical analysis of the series reveals a robust increasing trend across the entire duration. Rolling Mann-Kendall tests across six sequential windows (covering time steps 0 through 29) all return a significant increasing trend (p=0.027, tau=1.000). Although the general direction is strictly positive, the rate of change fluctuates, marked by identified inflection points at time steps 4, 6, 16, 19, 22, 28, and 31. The overall mean deviation for the series is 0.4965 with a median of 0.5584 and a standard deviation of 0.1702.\n\nWithin the context of the milk consumption model, this increasing deviation indicates a growing divergence between the agents' internal health valuations and the health implications of their selected milk types over the simulated historical period. Starting from a baseline of zero deviation, the gap widens systematically despite agents operating under constraints such as a memory lifetime of 5 and social susceptibility of 0.28. The parameters governing justification (0.61) and cognitive dissonance (0.15) interact with the network effects to produce this widening gap. By the end of the simulation, representing the shift in consumption patterns from the 1970s to 2005, the cumulative deviation reaches 0.7251, highlighting a persistent and statistically significant misalignment between stated health values and realized choices throughout the modeled years."
}

